<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:333px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Breakdown_of_objects_into_Geons.png" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/28/Breakdown_of_objects_into_Geons.png/331px-Breakdown_of_objects_into_Geons.png" decoding="async" width="331" height="200" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/28/Breakdown_of_objects_into_Geons.png/497px-Breakdown_of_objects_into_Geons.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/2/28/Breakdown_of_objects_into_Geons.png 2x" data-file-width="632" data-file-height="382" /></a>  <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Breakdown_of_objects_into_Geons.png" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>Breakdown of objects into geons</div></div></div>
<p>The <b>recognition-by-components theory</b>, or <b>RBC theory</b>,<sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> is a bottom-up process proposed by <a href="/wiki/Irving_Biederman" title="Irving Biederman">Irving Biederman</a> in 1987 to explain object recognition. According to RBC theory, we are able to recognize objects by separating them into <i><a href="/wiki/Geon_(psychology)" title="Geon (psychology)">geons</a></i> (the object’s main component parts). Biederman suggested that geons are based on basic 3-dimensional shapes (cylinders, cones, etc.) that can be assembled in various arrangements to form a virtually unlimited number of objects.<sup id="cite_ref-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-2">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<div id="toc" class="toc"><input type="checkbox" role="button" id="toctogglecheckbox" class="toctogglecheckbox" style="display:none" /><div class="toctitle" lang="en" dir="ltr"><h2>Contents</h2><span class="toctogglespan"><label class="toctogglelabel" for="toctogglecheckbox"></label></span></div>
